node.text:
Here we have the Dongchuan Red Soil “Red Land”.

An example of how the natural chemistry of the earth may generate extraordinary landscapes is this beautiful farmland in China.

Iron is abundant in the soil, which oxidizes in the air and turns the soil red. Iron is one of the most prevalent elements on the globe; it is required for plant growth and reproduction, but excessive amounts can be poisonous.

Some plants, on the other hand, have evolved to thrive in iron-rich soils which tend to be more acidic.
​
​Image credit: Su Jianfei/Shutterstock.

node.text:
50 years ago today humans drove the first car on the Moon.

OK, Moon buggy, but still. On July 31, 1971, astronauts David Scott and Jim Irwin became the first humans to drive on the Moon in a Lunar Roving Vehicle (LRV) as part of the Apollo 15 mission. 

Scott and Irwin logged 18.5 hours of exploration, collected samples, and completed three trips in the lunar buggy, a lightweight, battery-powered electric car, covering 17.5 miles and sending some pretty stunning images back to Earth.

All went smoothly, except for a small problem with the front-wheel steering, meaning they could only use rear-wheel steering. The following day the problem was fixed, prompting Scott to ask Joe Allen at Mission Control: “You know what I bet you did last night, Joe? You had some of those Marshall [Flight Center] guys come up here and fix it didn’t you?” 
​
​Image credit: NASA

node.text:
Compared to other athletes, long-distance runners and walkers poop themselves an extraordinary amount.

In 2016, French walker Yohann Diniz soiled himself, and heroically continued, and was able to finish in eighth place, despite fainting several times due to his gastrointestinal distress. Paula Radcliffe stopped by the roadside during the 2005 London Marathon to relieve herself, while cameras caught the whole incident on camera.

node.text:
Happy #FungiFriday! Strawberries and cream fungus, bleeding tooth fungus, and Devil's tooth are all common names for Hydnellum peckii, which has a distinctive pale velvety top and looks like it’s bleeding from its pores when it is young.

Scientists discovered that extracts from the fungus contain the chemical component atromentin, which has anti-bacterial and anti-coagulant capabilities.

H. peckii is native to Europe and the Pacific Northwest of North America, and despite its look, is nontoxic but inedible due to being extremely bitter. It’s also a mycorrhizal fungus, which means it has a beneficial association with specific tree roots. In exchange for boosting the tree's mineral absorption, the fungus receives fixed carbon from the host tree.
​
​Image credit: Henri Koskinen/Shutterstock.

Check out this cute candy-colored fuzzy moth! It’s the rosy maple moth (Dryocampa rubicunda) which as the name suggests, its favorite host tree is the maple tree.

The rosy maple is the smallest of the silk moths having a wingspan of about a golf ball. What it lacks in size, however, it makes up for in appetite. Silk moths do not feed as adults, but their young have been known to remove entire trees of leaves in areas where caterpillar populations are large.

node.text:
A 32-year-old murder case that many considered unsolvable has finally been brought to a resolution – and it all came down to the equivalent of just 15 human cells.

While the techniques that made the achievement possible are not new, what made this case truly extraordinary was the amount of DNA that was available: just 0.12 nanograms. That is less than for any case in history – to put the achievement into perspective, the amount of DNA used by commercially available tests is about 750 to 1,000 nanograms.
​
​​​​Read the whole story by clicking on this image post via the link in our bio. 🚀

node.text:
An adult European shag (Phalacrocorax aristotelis) exposing its big erected crest. We’re talking about the bird; behave.

The European shag, also known as a common shag, is a species of cormorant normally found on the rocky coasts of western and southern Europe, North Africa, and southwest Asia. They are one of the deepest divers among the cormorant family, reaching depths as deep as 45 meters when hunting for food.
​

This tiny adorable guy is a spiny orb-weaver spider!

Measuring around 2-9mm in length, these spiky spiders come in a variety of colors and shapes. There are many different species of spiny orb-weavers, all belonging to the genus Gasteracantha. This one is G. cancriformis, found across the United States, Central America, and the Caribbean.

node.text:
Happy #InternationalTigerDay! Known for being the national animal of India, tigers are the largest cat species in the world, reaching up to 3.3 meters in length and weighing up to 204 kilograms.

International Tiger Day was created to raise awareness for this critically endangered species and what we can do to help them. The population of tigers has dropped by more than 95% since the beginning of the 20th century due to several factors such as illegal wildlife trade and habitat loss.

2022 is the Chinese year of the Tiger, the year the WWF aims to help double the number of wild tigers to over 6,000 by. Currently, there are roughly 3,900 tigers in the wild, with around 3,000 in India.
​
​Image credit: dptro/Shutterstock, Bhanu Tej Prakash/Shutterstock, Ksenya_89/Shutterstock.
